comments.body:
slightly unrelated: Checking the different options, it's not always trivial to assess what negation would mean, but
```C++
    if (gArgs.IsArgSet("-color")) {
        const std::string color{gArgs.GetArg("-color", DEFAULT_COLOR_SETTING)};
        if (color == "always") {
            should_colorize = true;
        } else if (color == "never") {
            should_colorize = false;
        } else if (color != "auto") {
            throw std::runtime_error("Invalid value for -color option. Valid values: always, auto, never.");
        }
    }
```
Indicated that a `-nocolor` == `-color=never` could make sense.
Or is the `ArgsManager::DISALLOW_NEGATION` meant to discourage people from requesting that :D?

